<div id="review_1289097446" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1289097446" />
    <a title="Jake Goretzki" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/7556728-jake-goretzki"><img alt="Jake Goretzki" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1353432253p2/7556728.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1289097446?book_show_action=true">May 25, 2015</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Jake Goretzki" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Jake Goretzki" href="/user/show/7556728-jake-goretzki">Jake Goretzki</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was ok"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was ok</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/7556728-jake-goretzki?shelf=2015">2015</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1289097446" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer15167206826550464037">Clearly - from the blurb and the plaudits - this is an &apos;important work&apos; - and my failure to &apos;get it&apos; is a failure to police my mind (or something). Ominously, it got rave reviews from Hilton Als - whose recent memoir gave me similar migraines. <br/><br/><br/>I did find moments of lucidity (on Serena Williams; on everyday racism; on Zidane). But for the most part, I found this terribly self-indulgent, formless adolescent gloop that felt like listening to a cultural studies student breathlessly talking about las</span>
  <span id="freeText15167206826550464037" style="display:none">Clearly - from the blurb and the plaudits - this is an 'important work' - and my failure to 'get it' is a failure to police my mind (or something). Ominously, it got rave reviews from Hilton Als - whose recent memoir gave me similar migraines. <br /><br /><br />I did find moments of lucidity (on Serena Williams; on everyday racism; on Zidane). But for the most part, I found this terribly self-indulgent, formless adolescent gloop that felt like listening to a cultural studies student breathlessly talking about last night's dream in a therapy session. <br /><br />Things like this:<br /><br />"Do feelings lose their feeling if they speak to a lack of feeling? Can feelings be a hazard, a warning sign, a disturbance, distaste, the disgrace? Don't feel like you are mistaken. It's not that (Is it not that?) you are oversensitive or misunderstanding". <br /><br />And:<br /><br />"That time and that time and that time the outside blistered the inside of you, words outmaneuvered years, had you in a chokehold, every part roughed up, the eyes dripping" <br /><br />Confronted by these kind of witterings, I always want to break the silence and say: "Anyone know what time the Victoria line stops running?". <br /><br />I hate this kind of material. Every other line, I'm shouting: "what are you talking about? What has happened? What are you trying to say? What is 'The memory of a memory isn't a memory, but it cuts to the soul and bares forth the fruit of the ghost of a passion, leaving the cold imprint of a leaden shadow hanging on the heart's beat'". [I just made that last sentence up. But you'd never know, would you?]. <br /><br />PS: re Hackney rioters and Mark Duggan. If you think Mark Duggan equals Rodney King, you probably ought to check your sources too. <br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="15167206826550464037" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


